The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | HCL profit up 10%
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       HCL profit up 10%
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	Mumbai, April 15: Delhi-based software services firm HCL Technologies has clocked a standalone net profit of Rs 263.08 crore in the third quarter ended March 31 against Rs 238.59 crore a year ago, a 10.26 per cent rise.        
	The companys standalone total income rose to Rs 1,311.83 crore during the period from Rs 1,023.37 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year.         
	HCL today announced a third interim dividend of 100 per cent (Rs 2 on shares of Rs 2 each).         
	This was a quarter of consolidation for the BPO division. We managed to sustain our profitability in spite of pressures on margins. Attrition was at its lowest and 1,374 employees joined during this quarter, said Ranjit Narasimhan, president and chief executive officer (BPO services) of HCL Technologies.        
	According to the accounting norms in the US, the group posted a net income of $85.4 million in the reporting quarter compared with $76.2 million in the corresponding quarter a year ago.         
	Total revenues rose to $484.9 million for the quarter against $362.4 million in the year-ago period. HCL also signed deals worth $500 million during the quarter.         
	The HCL strategy embodies disruptive innovation in its business model, focusing on value centricity and internal organisation. It has resulted in deeper customer relationships and strategic partnerships, goal alignment and substantive engagement, said Shiv Nadar, chairman and chief strategy officer of HCL.         
	The company recorded a foreign exchange loss of Rs 27 crore during the quarter compared with a gain of Rs 41 crore in the same quarter a year ago.                                                                                                                                     
